-Docker
Docker is a platform that allows you to package an application and its dependencies into a container so it can run consistently on any system.

👉 Docker puts everything into a container (a box 📦):
	•	Code
	•	Libraries
	•	Dependencies
	•	Runtime
✔ So it runs the same everywhere
Why Use Docker?
🔹 Consistency
	•	Works same on dev, test, prod

🔹 Portability
	•	Run anywhere (cloud, local, server)

🔹 Isolation
	•	No conflicts between projects

🔹 Easy Deployment
	•	Faster CI/CD pipelines ﻿ ﻿ ﻿ ﻿




-kubernetes

Docker → Creates containers (your app)
Kubernetes → Manages those containers
💡 What Kubernetes Does
🔹 1. Auto Scaling
👉 More users → creates more containers 👉 Less users → reduces containers

🔹 2. Self-Healing
👉 If a container crashes ➡️ Kubernetes automatically restarts it

🔹 3. Load Balancing
👉 Distributes traffic across containers ➡️ No overload

🔹 4. Deployment Management
👉 Update app without downtime

💻 Example (Your Django Project)
Without Kubernetes:
	•	You manually run containers
	•	Handle scaling yourself
With Kubernetes:
	•	It automatically:
	◦	Runs multiple Django containers
	◦	Scales based on traffic
	◦	Restarts failed ones

🧱 Basic Components (Simple Terms)
🔹 Pod
Smallest unit (1 or more containers)

🔹 Node
A machine (server)

🔹 Cluster
Group of nodes

🔹 Deployment
Manages pods (scaling, updates)

🔄 Real Flow
	1	You deploy your app
	2	Kubernetes creates containers (pods)
	3	Users send requests
	4	Kubernetes balances traffic
	5	If something fails → it fixes it ﻿ ﻿ ﻿ ﻿ ﻿ ﻿




-Jenkins, 
Jenkins is an open-source automation tool used for implementing CI/CD pipelines. It automates building, testing, and deploying applications, helping teams deliver code faster and more reliably.

Jenkins pipeline:
	1	Pull latest code
	2	Build Docker image
	3	Run tests
	4	Deploy to server / Kubernetes

gitlab CI/CD 

CI/CD Pipeline defines:
	1	Pull code
	2	Install dependencies
	3	Run tests
	4	Build app
	5	Deploy
Jenkins does:
	•	Watches repo
	•	Triggers pipeline
	•	Executes each step
	•	Reports success/failure

